  <h1> General Facts About Scotland </h1>
  <p style= "float: right; clear: left"><img src="https://www.worldatlas.com/img/areamap/4e5207e1e945ebf963de3d3d4b6bb152.gif" align="right" alt="Image" height="450" width="325" border= "5 px">
  <p>Scotland is a part of the United Kingdom. It is home to around 800 small islands, notable ones being the northern
  isles of Shetland and Orkney, the Hebrides, etc. Scotland is surrounded by a various bodies of waters including the 
  North Sea in the east, the Atlantic Ocean in the north and west, and the Irish Sea in the south-west. Scotland is known for
  the countries beautiful highlands, vivid nature, and fascinating culture with a rich medieval history.
  It’s not hard to see why the national animal of Scotland is the Unicorn, as it is truly a magical country.

  <p> The main reason why thousands of people travel to Scotland for their summer holiday is: Nature! No matter where you go in Scotland, you should be able to find natural reserves, 
  cycling paths, national parks, scenic areas, geoparks, and many other outdoor events. </p>
  <p> Some of the most famous ones are:  </p>
